  "business_context": "Order records mark the transition from \"potential sale\" to \"committed sale.\" Once a customer accepts a quote (or places a direct order), an Order record captures the confirmed details: what they're buying, in what quantities, at what price, shipping where, billing where, with what terms. Orders drive fulfillment workflows (ship the goods, deliver the service, provision the subscription) and billing workflows (generate the invoice, schedule recurring billing). Salesforce introduced the Order object in Spring '14 to fill this gap between Opportunity and Invoice. Many older deployments don't use Orders — they go directly from won Opportunity to invoicing in their ERP. EspoCRM has Sales Order (with Sales Order Item line items). HubSpot has Quotes + Line Items rather than a separate Order entity. Attio has no native Order. CiviCRM has no Order — Contributions cover the donation case directly. Nonprofit deployments rarely use Orders. When interviewing clients, surface \"Order\" by asking whether they need to track confirmed-sale fulfillment separately from quoting and from invoicing. Many B2B deployments skip the Order layer; pure-services orgs almost always do; product-shipping orgs almost always need it.",
  "catalog_id": "order",
  "common_synonyms": [
    "Sales Order",
    "Purchase Order (when the org is the seller)",
    "Confirmed Order"
  ],
